{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499742"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:02:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1539"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1539"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.04,0.06,0.51,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86740"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1539"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71009"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29774"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86740"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man from Turkey presents with a one month history of right upper quadrant pain and lethargy. The pain is associated with nausea and vomiting. He does not drink any alcohol and has a 20 pack-year smoking history. On examination his blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg, pulse 80/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. He does not appear anaemic, nor is there any icterus. On abdominal examination there is tenderness in the right upper quadrant region. There is no jaundice. An abdominal CT is performed and a representative image is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathogens is most the likely underlying cause of his current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Entamoeba histolytica","Escherichia coli","Trypanosoma cruzi","Echinococcus granulosis","Wuchereria bancrofti"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a 10 cm compartmentalised cystic lesion in the right lobe of the liver. This is the typical appearance of a hydatid cyst containing daughter cysts. These cysts result from infestation of the intermediate host (humans) by inadvertent ingestion of eggs from the tapeworm \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E which lives in the intestines of the definitive host (usually dogs). Turkey is one of the regions where hydatid disease is endemic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E typically cause liver abscesses. These would appear as single or multiple fluid collections, often with surrounding inflammation, but would not show the characteristic compartmentalised appearance with daughter cysts seen in hydatid disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrypanosoma cruzi\u003C/strong\u003E is found in South and Central America and causes Chagas disease, primarily affecting the heart and gastrointestinal tract rather than forming liver cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWuchereria bancrofti\u003C/strong\u003E is a filarial nematode that lives in lymphatic vessels, causing lymphatic obstruction and elephantiasis. It does not cause liver lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/strong\u003E infection is supported by the patient\u0027s origin from an endemic area, the characteristic imaging appearance, and the relatively indolent presentation. Treatment typically involves a combination of antiparasitic medication (albendazole) and careful surgical removal to prevent cyst rupture and anaphylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Multiloculated cystic lesions in the liver are usually due to Echinococcus infection."],"references":["Keong B, Wilkie B, Sutherland T, et al. Hepatic cystic echinococcosis in Australia: an update on diagnosis and management. ANZ J Surg 2018; 88:26\u201331"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71009"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1539"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19061"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19061"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9208f862-c3b5-4e6c-bc52-489f9d67c1d9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9208f862-c3b5-4e6c-bc52-489f9d67c1d9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":619,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71009"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-24T14:43:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-25T22:10:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1539"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86740"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relat